<h2>Specific climate indicators for January 2018</h2>
<br><br>
In most of Europe the number of warm days was larger than in the reference period 1981-2010 (Figure 3). As &rsquo;warm&rsquo; relates to the &#62;90 percentile range, the reference number of warm days per month is about 3. The number of warm days was particularly large in Italy and parts of Central Europe. In parts of Italy more than half of the days were warm days.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG90p_baselayers_overlay_2018-01-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG90p_baselayers_overlay_2018-01-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jan2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2018_month_nc__2018-01-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg90p_2018_month_nc__2018-01-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: Number of warm days in January 2018, where &rsquo;warm&rsquo; relates to the percentile range &#62;90 as calculated from the reference period 1981-2010. (Based on E-OBS)</em>
<br><br>
In most of Europe the number of frost days, with minimum temperature below zero, and the number of ice days, with maximum temperature below zero, was much smaller than in the reference period (Figure 4). In North-East Europe the number of ice days strongly decreased, but as the minimum temperature often still remained below zero, the decrease in the number of frost days was small. In Central Europe, on the other hand, where negative minimum temperatures were closer to zero, the decrease in the number of frost days was large.
<br><br>
