<strong>Evolution of the European land-surface temperature</strong>
<br><br>
Figure 9 (left panel) shows the European-averaged temperature from 1950 onward, where blue bars show temperatures which are below the 1981-2010 average and red bars above this mean value. The green bar is the provisional 2018 estimate, based on data until the end of January and climatological means for the remaining months. The grey bars in the panel indicate the estimated uncertainties which take into account the errors introduced by spatial interpolation over areas without observation stations, inhomogeneities in the temperature data that result from station relocations / changes in measurement instruments etc., and biases due to urbanisation, as documented in Van der Schrier et al. (2013) and Chrysanthou et al. (2014). The uncertainties tell us that although we are not 100% certain about the ranking of individual years, the overall positive trend since the 1980s is very pronounced.
<br><br>
The right panel of Figure 9 shows the daily temperature, averaged over Europe, for the past 12 months as the deviation form the long-term (1981-2010) daily mean.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2018/EuropeanAverage_annual_2017_wrt81-10_201801.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2018/EuropeanAverage_annual_2017_wrt81-10_201801.png" width="250px"></a>
<a href="../images/jan2018/Dailyanomalies_201801.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2018/Dailyanomalies_201801.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 9: European land surface temperature: annual anomalies with the current year in green. The grey bands show the uncertainty in the averaged temperature (left). Daily anomalies with respect to the seasonal cycle until the end of January 2018 (right).</em>
<br><br>
<h3>Precipitation</h3>
<br><br>
In January 2018 precipitation over Europe was very irregular distributed. The highest monthly amounts occurred in Central Europe, in Germany (maximum of 541 mm/month), Norway (maximum of 458 mm/month), the United Kingdom (321 mm/month) and Spain (316 mm/month). The most significant precipitation occurred in Switzerland at the Valais in Col du Grand St-Bernard (2472 m.a.s.l.) with 787 mm and Les Tsantons d'Otemma (2357 m.a.s.l.) with 693 mm. In these high mountains, however, the uncertainty due to snowdrifts is high. This high precipitation amounts together with snow melt led to high river levels and flooding while most parts of Italy, Spain and Scandinavia had a lack of rain.
<br><br>
The highest precipitation amount during 24 hours of more than 70 mm was registered in several countries in Central Europe, in Italy, Switzerland and Norway even more than 100 mm/d
<br><br>
<br><br>
